<p>The ranges below are common U.S. market figures and a useful starting point for budgeting. Final pricing is confirmed after reviewing project scope and intended use.</p>
<h2>Typical price ranges (2025, U.S.)</h2>
<div class="spec-table">
  <div class="r"><span class="l">Concept, massing, feasibility &amp; small residential</span><span class="v">$2,000 – $8,000</span></div>
  <div class="r"><span class="l">Townhomes, small commercial &amp; moderate-detail site models</span><span class="v">$4,000 – $20,000</span></div>
  <div class="r"><span class="l">Sales galleries, luxury developments &amp; high-detail presentations</span><span class="v">$15,000 – $80,000+</span></div>
  <div class="r"><span class="l">Urban planning, industrial, campuses &amp; infrastructure</span><span class="v">$30,000 – $250,000+</span></div>
</div>
<h2>What drives the cost</h2>
<h3>Size &amp; scale</h3>
<p>Larger models require more materials, more components, and more fabrication time. A shift from 1:200 to 1:100 can roughly double the cost.</p>
<h3>Level of detail</h3>
<p>Fine façade details, furniture, landscaping, lighting, and realistic finishes all increase material and labor hours.</p>
<h3>Materials</h3>
<p>Costs change based on whether the model is built from ABS, acrylic, resin, engineered wood, or a mix of premium components.</p>
<h3>Special features</h3>
<p>LED lighting, interchangeable modules, transparent components, moving parts, and embedded electronics add to pricing.</p>
<h3>Timeline</h3>
<p>Rush projects use more labor overlap and extended machine hours, which increases the overall cost.</p>
<div class="callout">Because each model is custom-built, pricing can only be estimated once the design information is reviewed. Share your drawings and intended use for a clear quote.</div>
